Functions and Classes assignment

A function is a segment of code that can be called and repeated. In c++, creating a function looks like:

(return type) (name)(){
    code
}

ex.

void myFunc(){
    cout << "Hello world";
}

the return type allows for a function to return a specific type of variable, for instance, we can create an addition function that
returns the sum of two numbers. To do this, we also need to pass variables to the function:

int add(int num1, int num2) {
    return num1+num2;
}

int main(){
    int num1 = 6;
    add(5, num1);
}

The variables created in the function are seperate from all others, so you can reuse names if you want.
Functions are great for rapidly calling code that needs to be repeated many times in a program.


A class is a object similar to a variable, but has more features. It can have its own variables and functions, which are called methods.
Classes in c++ are created like this:

class myClass{
string name;

    myClass(string x){
        name = x
    }

    void classFunc(){
        cout << "Hello, my name is " << name;
    }

};

The first code segment is called a constructor, it is called when a class is created and defines some of the variables in it.
Creating a class in the main function looks like:

myClass Edward(edward);

If we want to call the method in the class, we do:

Edward.classFunc();